Ni$_{4}$B$_{3}$ is found in two forms (Rundqvist, 1967): \begin{itemize} \item This \href{current_web_home_dir/A3B4_oP28_62_3c_4c-001}{orthorhombic structure}, and \item a \href{current_web_home_dir/A3B4_mC28_15_ef_2f-001}{monoclinic structure}. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 While the monoclinic structure is stoichiometric, with chains of boron atoms, the composition of the orthorhombic phase is Ni$_{4}$B$_{3-x}$, with vacancies on the boron sites.  The exact phase depends on the stoichiometry. 
 \href{current_web_home_dir/A3B4_oP28_62_3c_4c-001}{Orthorhombic Ni$_{4}$B$_{3}$}, \href{current_web_home_dir/A3B4_oP28_62_3c_4c-002}{Rh$_{4}$P$_{3}$}, and \href{current_web_home_dir/A3B4_oP28_62_3c_4c-003}{Eu$_{3}$O$_{4}$} have the same AFLOW prototype label, A3B4\_oP28\_62\_3c\_4c. They are generated by the same symmetry operations with different sets of parameters ({\tt --params}) specified in their corresponding CIF files.
